		Comment <a href="#c_1713663750">9</a> by Peter J. Farrell
		posted on 4/3/2007 at 9:34 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>I lived in Montreal, Canada for a couple of years not too long ago.  My wife was in graduate school and since neither of us are Canadian citizens -- we were not covered by Quebec's provincial health coverage.  The only option for us for was to get coverage through the university with Blue Cross of Quebec.  Get this now...  We paid just shy of $1k USD for the BOTH of us for the ENTIRE year.  We had no co-pay for visits, no co-pay for Rx (with 100% coverage) and even an upgrade to a semi-private room for hospital stays (which is great since there are some hospitals that still have wards there).  All in all, this was private insurance as well and even the Canadians we knew complained that we paid WAY too much for coverage.</p><p>There's two reason in my mind why they can keep premiums downs. 1) The government sets the rates for procedures and visits and 2) the government negotiates drug prices each year and sets the selling price.  (Another is that drug patent laws are different there - so there's competition with the generic makers.)</p><p>This leads to a couple of things.  Since there is equal access to doctors, "bad" doctors (which diagnose not so well, maybe grumpy, etc.) loose patients.  If you want to do well, you have to practice medicine well.  I'd say that the quality of service was better than in the states.  However I'm sure people will disagree with me.  Maybe I'm an idealist, but let's all be human here - doesn't everybody have a right to health?</p></div>
