		Comment <a href="#c_1713663757">15</a> by C. Steven Tucker
		posted on 4/7/2007 at 6:35 AM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>I have been a health insurance broker for over a decade and every day I hear more and more horror stories like the ones posted regarding insurance companies not paying claims or refusing to cover specific illnesses and physician's not getting reimbursed. Unfortunately, the reality is that insurance companies are driven by profits, not people. If the insurance company can find a legal reason not to pay for something, chances are they will find it, and you, the CONSUMER will suffer. However, very few reasons exist. The majority of the time the insured has no idea that they purchased a plan with a variety of exclusions or payment caps and because these caps or exclusions are in writing in the policy, the insured has no legal recourse because they signed the paperwork and accepted the policy oftentimes blindly trusting the agent. So the insurance company wins again.</p><p>We can all complain about insurance companies but they are a necessary evil. Very few of us in this day and age would consider going without health insurance. This being the case, how then can you protect yourself from insurance companies, and how will you really know if you are getting the best plan for the lowest price? I have read the comments about the 100% plans and I agree that they have a great appeal. However, I would not recommend working overtime and giving up time with your family just to be able to afford a plan with 100% coverage. Everyone wants to have affordable, quality health coverage, but in my experience, particularly dealing with the small business and self-employed market, very few people want to take the time to educate themselves about health insurance. This is one of the primary reasons that most people feel like they have been defrauded or "ripped-off."</p><p>As a broker, I make calls to business owners all the time. Time and time again, I ask the same "BASIC" questions regarding the health plan that they currently have in place and 100% of the time, no one can answer all the following questions.</p><p>1. What Insurance Company are you with and what is the name of your plan?<br>2. What is your deductible?<br>3. What is your coinsurance percentage?<br>4. What is your stop loss number? (This determines your maximum out of pocket expense per year). <br>5. What is the Lifetime maximum benefit the insurance company will pay out if you become seriously ill?  <br>6.)Are there any "per illness" limits on your plan? <br>7.)Did you really buy a legitimate major medical plan or did you instead purchase a schedule plan which only pays a certain amount and nothing more per procedure? (example: Mega Life &amp; Health &amp; Midwest National Life a.k.a. N.A.S.E.<br>8. Does your plan offer any outpatient doctor copays and how much are they? If you have them are they limited?<br>9. Does your plan offer outpatient prescription drug coverage and if it does, do you pay a copay or do you have to meet a separate drug deductible before you receive any benefits?<br>8. Does your plan have a reduction in benefits for organ transplants? <br>9. Do you have to pay any separate deductibles on your plan if you need hospitalization or emergency room services?<br>10. Are there any restrictions/limits on out-patient services, such as, physical therapy, speech therapy, etc. or are there separate "access" fees for these services?</p><p>If you can't answer all ten questions either, does that mean you are not a smart consumer? No! It just means that you have a "bad" agent. A great agent will really take the time to help you understand your health insurance benefits. A great agent looks out for YOUR best interest and NOT the interest of the insurance company.</p><p>So how do you know if you have a "great" agent? If you can answer all of the above questions without looking at your policy, you have a "great" agent. If you can't you don't.  Just like any other profession, there are professionals that really care about the clients they work with and there are others who will never return phone calls when you have a question or a problem.</p><p>Considering that Health Insurance is one of the most important "buying" decisions that we are likely to make, why do most of us know so little about what we purchased?</p><p>Unlike car buying, where you assume that an engine, transmission and air-conditioner is standard, health insurance is a maze of confusion where "nothing" may be standard. When purchasing health insurance, the "transmission" may be an option. If you have every option you can think of (100% Coverage) but are relatively healthy and rarely go to the doctor, is it worth giving the insurance company an extra $200 per month or is it better to save that money, just in case you have to pay out of pocket? Remember, there is no bonus or refund of premiums for staying healthy....but is it really in your best interest to have to work overtime to afford your health plan?</p><p>To be an informed consumer, you have to ask a lot of questions and feel comfortable with the answers that you receive. Read the fine print in your health plan brochure and make sure you find out what every asterisk next to the benefit description really means. Do an internet search for lawsuits against that company. If the original poster would have researched MEGA Life and Health, aka Midwest National Life a.k.a. National Association for the Self Employed (N.A.S.E) a.k.a. Alliance for affordable services (all U.I.C.I. companies)he would have noticed the 14 class action lawsuits brought against them since 1995. In turn, he probably would not have bought a policy from them in the first place.</p><p>If you have concerns about an insurance company, in regards to complaints or non-payment of claims, call your state's Department of Insurance and find out how many complaints have been made against the insurance carrier by other policy holders. If you think your agent is trying to rip you off or you are concerned about insurance fraud, ask the Department of Insurance if there have been any complaints made against that agent.</p><p>There are a lot of things you can do become an educated consumer and make good solid buying decisions. And always remember....."if it sounds too could to be true, it probably is!"</p><p>-C. Steven Tucker<br>Licensed Insurance Agent<br>Small Business Insurance Services, Inc.<br>"The Best Policy Is A Great Agent"<br><a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.smallbusinessinsuranceservices.com%3A_2mjl1Gv2tqqBbIt67ahyn5oXEU&amp;cuid=3321886" rel="nofollow noopener" title="www.smallbusinessinsuranceservices.com">www.smallbusinessinsurances...</a><br>Call Toll Free: (866) SBIS123 (724-7123)</p></div>
